00:24:40,200 --> 00:24:42,080
Rym: And it was on the news for him constantly.

402
00:24:43,808 --> 00:24:44,539
Scott: What year was this?

403
00:24:45,060 --> 00:24:45,724
Rym: Like, recently.

404
00:24:45,744 --> 00:24:46,872
Rym: Early 2000s.

405
00:24:49,182 --> 00:24:51,374
Scott: If you saw that on the news, I think it was a fake news.

406
00:24:51,415 --> 00:24:52,360
Scott: I wouldn't think it was real news.

407
00:24:52,821 --> 00:24:53,905
Rym: Well, it was all in the background.

408
00:24:53,945 --> 00:24:58,200
Rym: It'd be like normal news, normal news, and then there'd be this one thing just planted in the news.

409
00:24:58,881 --> 00:25:01,740
Scott: Yeah, there's no way a smart person believes that.

410
00:25:01,820 --> 00:25:03,500
Rym: So, we didn't think about it too much, I assume.

411
00:25:03,881 --> 00:25:10,780
Rym: But then the event was, they ostensibly had flown him out to Japan to try to beat a race walking world record in an empty stadium.

412
00:25:10,841 --> 00:25:12,520
Scott: Was this guy a race walking record holder?

413
00:25:12,861 --> 00:25:15,039
Rym: He is a professional race walker of some kind.

414
00:25:16,963 --> 00:25:18,660
Rym: And they had him doing his race walking.

415
00:25:19,520 --> 00:25:25,680
Rym: And then they had a bunch of people dressed up as samurai bust in and they had a bunch of blood squibs and everything.

416
00:25:26,040 --> 00:25:27,940
Rym: So, as he's running by, there's this kind of commotion.

417
00:25:28,360 --> 00:25:31,440
Rym: And he sees this guy dressed up as samurai yelling at some cops and things.

418
00:25:31,800 --> 00:25:35,100
Rym: And then the samurai murder these dudes and he's still race walking.

419
00:25:35,721 --> 00:25:37,032
Rym: And then the samurai go, "Oh,

420
00:25:37,314 --> 00:25:37,456
Rym: oh!".

421
00:25:37,516 --> 00:25:37,960
Rym: and they point.

422
00:25:38,661 --> 00:25:40,019
Rym: And then they start running after him.

423
00:25:40,521 --> 00:25:47,840
Rym: And the whole point of this is a bunch of people watching this on monitors betting on whether or not he will run or walk away.

424
00:25:49,121 --> 00:25:51,798
Rym: Will he race walk away or will he give up and run?

425
00:25:52,720 --> 00:25:56,140
Scott: It pretty much comes down to if he believes it's fake, he's just going to keep doing his race walk.

426
00:25:56,440 --> 00:25:57,160
Rym: But then they come after him.

427
00:25:57,300 --> 00:26:00,380
Scott: If he doesn't believe it's fake, he's just going to run because he doesn't care about the race walk anymore.

428
00:26:00,460 --> 00:26:02,719
Rym: So, when they come after him, he starts to race walk a little bit.

429
00:26:03,120 --> 00:26:05,059
Rym: And then, spoilers, he runs.

430
00:26:06,340 --> 00:26:08,059
Scott: I mean, technically he was running the whole time.

431
00:26:08,244 --> 00:26:08,594
Rym: Well, yeah.

432
00:26:12,002 --> 00:26:13,355
Rym: So, yeah.

433
00:26:13,517 --> 00:26:13,800
Rym: Theben.

434
00:26:14,820 --> 00:26:15,659
Scott: Yeah, so here's a game.

435
00:26:15,980 --> 00:26:17,700
Scott: And I did a little bit of research on this game.

436
00:26:17,820 --> 00:26:19,234
Scott: So, it was printed a long time ago.

437
00:26:19,255 --> 00:26:19,760
Scott: What year?

438
00:26:21,040 --> 00:26:21,760
Scott: That's a long time ago.

439
00:26:22,322 --> 00:26:24,837
Rym: The box art looks like it's an early 90s game, though.

440
00:26:25,321 --> 00:26:26,039
Rym: I mean, look at that box.

441
00:26:26,260 --> 00:26:27,560
Scott: Yeah, it looks like an even older game.

442
00:26:27,700 --> 00:26:29,740
Scott: But the game was called Gensites von Theben.

443
00:26:29,860 --> 00:26:32,260
Scott: Does gensites mean archaeologists or something like that?

444
00:26:32,920 --> 00:26:33,671
Rym: Archaeological sites?

445
00:26:33,692 --> 00:26:34,219
Rym: I don't know.

446
00:26:34,300 --> 00:26:35,120
Scott: Yeah, something like that.

447
00:26:35,180 --> 00:26:36,920
Scott: And archaeological von Peterprins.

448
00:26:37,245 --> 00:26:37,490
Scott: Right.

449
00:26:37,531 --> 00:26:38,020
Scott: So, anyway.

450
00:26:38,861 --> 00:26:39,939
Rym: For two to four spieler.

451
00:26:40,860 --> 00:26:43,636
Scott: So, the game was reprinted in a much better version.

452
00:26:43,677 --> 00:26:44,099
Scott: in what year?

453
00:26:45,240 --> 00:26:45,703
Rym: Oh, sorry.

454
00:26:45,743 --> 00:26:46,951
Rym: For ages 10 and up.

455
00:26:46,971 --> 00:26:48,360
Rym: I'm trying to read those old German rules.

456
00:26:48,541 --> 00:26:49,160
Scott: Yeah, we don't care about that.

457
00:26:49,160 --> 00:26:50,671
Rym: It was reprinted in 2007 as just Thebes.

458
00:26:52,020 --> 00:26:54,920
Scott: So, I think it's hard to get and out of print, maybe.

459
00:26:55,181 --> 00:26:56,536
Scott: But, maybe it's not hard to get.

460
00:26:56,576 --> 00:26:56,900
Scott: I don't know.

461
00:26:57,885 --> 00:26:59,676
Scott: But, we had a friend had a copy.

462
00:26:59,716 --> 00:27:00,360
Scott: We played it a bunch.

463
00:27:00,420 --> 00:27:03,440
Scott: It's a game I had seen around before at conventions and in game libraries.

464
00:27:03,901 --> 00:27:05,060
Scott: And never had actually played.

465
00:27:05,583 --> 00:27:06,429
Scott: So, we played it.

466
00:27:06,529 --> 00:27:08,140
Scott: We played it like two or three times.

467
00:27:08,320 --> 00:27:11,860
Rym: Well, Scott played it and then he comes over to me later because I was doing something else.

468
00:27:11,940 --> 00:27:13,294
Rym: He's like, "Oh my god, we're going to play this digging

469
00:27:13,314 --> 00:27:13,537
Rym: game.".

470
00:27:13,940 --> 00:27:14,965
Rym: And he kept bringing it up.

471
00:27:15,327 --> 00:27:17,940
Rym: And then, like the next day, I played the digging game and we dug.

472
00:27:18,240 --> 00:27:22,280
Scott: So, the thing about this game is that it's just so thematically good, right?

473
00:27:22,560 --> 00:27:23,706
Scott: The theme of the game is this.

474
00:27:23,767 --> 00:27:26,220
Scott: You are an archaeologist, like Indiana Jones style.

475
00:27:26,420 --> 00:27:27,260
Rym: Yeah, fake archaeologist.

476
00:27:27,742 --> 00:27:29,740
Scott: Except without the traps and the golden monkeys and shit.

477
00:27:29,740 --> 00:27:32,275
Rym: The little dudes you move around have Indiana Jones.

478
00:27:32,295 --> 00:27:33,180
Rym: They're just Indiana Jones.

479
00:27:33,280 --> 00:27:33,461
Rym: Right.

480
00:27:33,822 --> 00:27:39,460
Scott: So, you start in yerp and you're going around yerp researching things, right?

481
00:27:39,782 --> 00:27:40,960
Rym: And chasing down rumors.

482
00:27:41,680 --> 00:27:46,775
Scott: Right, or you're hiring diggers or getting graduate students to follow you around.

483
00:27:48,900 --> 00:27:52,900
Rym: Maybe you're buying a blimp to keep on hand or you buy a car, which apparently is super awesome.

484
00:27:53,340 --> 00:27:54,440
Scott: Yeah, which we didn't think was awesome.

485
00:27:54,701 --> 00:27:55,960
Rym: You didn't think was awesome.

486
00:27:56,020 --> 00:27:57,540
Scott: Well, I was told it was not awesome.

487
00:27:57,700 --> 00:28:00,159
Rym: Yeah, we'll talk about this later, but we started the game and Scott's like,

488
00:28:00,179 --> 00:28:00,220
Rym: "Oh.".

489
00:28:00,280 --> 00:28:01,079
Rym: I trusted someone.

490
00:28:01,241 --> 00:28:02,990
Rym: The car comes up and Scott's like, "Oh, the car

491
00:28:03,111 --> 00:28:03,473
Rym: sucks.".

492
00:28:03,533 --> 00:28:04,519
Rym: And I'm like, "Well...".

493
00:28:04,861 --> 00:28:07,640
Scott: I was told the car sucked, but apparently that was not the case.

494
00:28:07,840 --> 00:28:11,019
Rym: The car would probably be pretty great if I bought it in the beginning of the game and then a car appears.

495
00:28:11,420 --> 00:28:12,760
Rym: And, of course, our friend buys it right away.

496
00:28:12,820 --> 00:28:16,136
Scott: I was also told the shovel was awesome, so I got a bunch of shovels right away.

497
00:28:16,157 --> 00:28:16,840
Scott: Not that awesome.

498
00:28:17,300 --> 00:28:18,811
Rym: Yeah, the shovel was awesome, but you know what?

499
00:28:18,872 --> 00:28:19,778
Rym: I only got two shovels.

500
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:21,980
Scott: I got three and it still wasn't awesome enough.

501
00:28:22,601 --> 00:28:24,319
Scott: Anyway, so here's how the game works.

502
00:28:25,741 --> 00:28:27,106
Scott: You spend time.

503
00:28:27,166 --> 00:28:30,560
Scott: The game, depending on how many players you have, is two or three years long.

504
00:28:31,022 --> 00:28:35,920
Scott: And everything you do takes time, so you move along the edge of the board whenever you do anything.

505
00:28:36,160 --> 00:28:38,840
Rym: Like where the victory point track is on regular German games.

506
00:28:39,160 --> 00:28:41,700
Rym: Instead, that's just time, so I do a thing.

507
00:28:41,860 --> 00:28:43,840
Scott: There's 52 weeks in the year, so you move.

508
00:28:44,421 --> 00:28:52,537
Scott: If you do something that takes six weeks, it's like moving from Moscow to London and then doing some research could take you one week per space.

509
00:28:52,558 --> 00:28:55,272
Scott: you have to move, which could be three spaces or four spaces.

510
00:28:55,373 --> 00:28:56,520
Scott: Moscow to London is pretty far.

511
00:28:57,102 --> 00:29:00,776
Scott: And then you spend time learning about Mesopotamia.

512
00:29:00,816 --> 00:29:01,780
Scott: That takes three more weeks.

513
00:29:01,960 --> 00:29:03,360
Rym: So like a card would be on a place.

514
00:29:03,660 --> 00:29:06,920
Scott: So you move your guy seven spaces because it took seven weeks.

515
00:29:07,701 --> 00:29:14,020
Rym: So some cards, like if you do a bunch of research in Moscow, even after you move to Moscow, you'll spend like six weeks doing the research.

516
00:29:14,462 --> 00:29:18,620
Rym: But if you just find some schmuck with a room around the street, it only takes like one more week.

517
00:29:19,141 --> 00:29:21,820
Rym: And you go until you run out of time.

518
00:29:21,900 --> 00:29:27,020
Scott: So whoever's turn it is is the person who has currently spent the least number of weeks.

519
00:29:27,420 --> 00:29:30,560
Scott: So if you've spent the least amount of time, you spend a little bit of time.

520
00:29:30,761 --> 00:29:33,760
Scott: And if you pass someone, they now spend a little bit of time.

521
00:29:33,820 --> 00:29:37,800
Scott: And everyone does a move whenever they're currently the person who's done the least stuff.

522
00:29:38,180 --> 00:29:39,860
Rym: So whoever's furthest back always takes their turn.

523
00:29:40,040 --> 00:29:42,040
Scott: So sometimes you can do stuff twice in a row.

524
00:29:42,060 --> 00:29:49,960
Scott: If you do a little bit and then a little bit and a little bit and everyone else has already done a whole ton of crap, then you can actually do a bunch of different things while everyone else is waiting for you.

525
00:29:49,980 --> 00:29:52,720
Rym: Now that in and of itself is a novel mechanic.

526
00:29:52,920 --> 00:29:53,885
Scott: It's so thematic.

527
00:29:53,926 --> 00:29:56,400
Scott: It's like you're spending time going around doing stuff.

528
00:29:56,620 --> 00:29:59,539
Scott: And everyone has the same amount of time to do stuff as everyone else.

529
00:29:59,900 --> 00:30:02,120
Scott: Because you can't end the game by going over or under.

530
00:30:02,520 --> 00:30:06,860
Scott: You end the game going exactly two or three years of stuff doing.

531
00:30:07,320 --> 00:30:12,580
Rym: But also as a mechanic, it is very novel because it provides a lot of...

532
00:30:12,580 --> 00:30:13,480
Scott: It solves the turn order problem.

533
00:30:13,780 --> 00:30:17,360
Rym: It provides a lot of opportunities for a clever game designer using a mechanic like this.

534
00:30:17,460 --> 00:30:20,197
Scott: It's something like, "Oh, you got to be the first player and I'm sitting to your

535
00:30:20,237 --> 00:30:20,499
Scott: left.".

536
00:30:20,680 --> 00:30:21,439
Scott: And none of that happens.

537
00:30:21,500 --> 00:30:24,940
Rym: To design a very well-balanced or self-balancing game.

538
00:30:25,120 --> 00:30:26,560
Rym: Because sure, the shovel's awesome.

539
00:30:27,100 --> 00:30:28,420
Rym: Shovel takes a lot of time.

540
00:30:28,520 --> 00:30:32,059
Rym: So you could do like a big crazy move on your turn.

541
00:30:32,563 --> 00:30:33,940
Rym: But it might take a ton of weeks.

542
00:30:34,341 --> 00:30:37,480
Rym: And then everyone else takes like three or four turns before you get to go again.

543
00:30:37,720 --> 00:30:37,942
Scott: Right.

544
00:30:37,962 --> 00:30:41,447
Scott: Now the other thing you do is you can go down below out of... You can leave Europe.

545
00:30:41,467 --> 00:30:42,980
Scott: You can go to... Well, Greece is still in Europe.

546
00:30:43,040 --> 00:30:47,380
Scott: But you can go to Greece, Crete, Egypt, Mesopotamia, Palestine.

547
00:30:47,481 --> 00:30:48,479
Scott: Is there somewhere else to go?

548
00:30:48,642 --> 00:30:49,000
Rym: I forget.

549
00:30:49,460 --> 00:30:49,561
Scott: Right.

550
00:30:49,621 --> 00:30:50,568
Scott: Rome is part of Europe.

551
00:30:50,608 --> 00:30:52,380
Scott: It's not part of the archaeology dig places.

552
00:30:52,460 --> 00:30:54,280
Scott: And you just go there the same way you go around Europe.

553
00:30:54,340 --> 00:30:56,539
Scott: But when you get there, there's only one thing to do.

554
00:30:56,924 --> 00:30:57,840
Scott: And that is start digging.

555
00:30:58,623 --> 00:30:59,696
Rym: Now the digging mechanic is...

556
00:31:00,700 --> 00:31:01,019
Scott: The best.

557
00:31:01,762 --> 00:31:04,620
Rym: Now it's the best, but at the same time it does make the game a little random.

558
00:31:05,300 --> 00:31:06,719
Scott: It makes the game a lot random.

559
00:31:06,880 --> 00:31:08,860
Rym: But it makes it thematically really fun.

560
00:31:08,860 --> 00:31:08,982
Scott: Right.

561
00:31:09,022 --> 00:31:10,280
Scott: This game is all about theme.

562
00:31:10,340 --> 00:31:12,620
Scott: It's not about being a strong competitive game.

563
00:31:13,083 --> 00:31:15,399
Rym: I've already come up with some pretty strong strategies, though.

564
00:31:15,620 --> 00:31:19,220
Scott: I mean, there's strong strategies, but in the end it's the mercy of the desert, right?

565
00:31:19,582 --> 00:31:20,680
Scott: So let's say you go to Egypt.

566
00:31:21,000 --> 00:31:22,287
Scott: And you've studied Egypt a lot.

567
00:31:22,307 --> 00:31:24,640
Scott: You've studied four Egypts, right?

568
00:31:25,160 --> 00:31:27,820
Scott: There's this little awesome wheel you use and you spin the wheel.

569
00:31:27,900 --> 00:31:30,115
Scott: And the wheel says, "Oh, you've studied four

570
00:31:30,276 --> 00:31:30,598
Scott: Egypts.".

571
00:31:31,000 --> 00:31:36,160
Scott: Well, if you dig in Egypt for eight weeks, you get to dig this much dirt in Egypt.

572
00:31:36,760 --> 00:31:41,380
Scott: And the more you know about Egypt or the more time you spend, the more you get to dig.

573
00:31:41,701 --> 00:31:45,460
Rym: So the bag that you dig from for each site, each site has its own bag.

574
00:31:45,580 --> 00:31:46,468
Scott: You literally dig.

575
00:31:46,489 --> 00:31:47,660
Scott: There's an Egypt bag.

576
00:31:48,340 --> 00:31:53,918
Scott: And you reach your hand in there and pull out a number of tiles equal to how many you're allowed to dig, right?

577
00:31:54,881 --> 00:31:56,420
Scott: And you're digging through that bag.

578
00:31:56,660 --> 00:32:00,640
Scott: And in the bag, it starts the game with half treasure and half dirt.

579
00:32:01,080 --> 00:32:03,240
Scott: Any treasure you get is treasure you get.

580
00:32:03,380 --> 00:32:04,619
Scott: And it's worth victory points.

581
00:32:04,720 --> 00:32:06,016
Scott: Any dirt you get is dirt.

582
00:32:06,500 --> 00:32:13,139
Scott: Now what makes the game amazing is that when you're done digging the Egypt bag, you take all the treasures and you keep them.

583
00:32:13,640 --> 00:32:16,379
Scott: You know, you might want to uphold an exhibition or who knows what you're going to do with them.

584
00:32:16,820 --> 00:32:19,414
Scott: But all the dirt goes back in.

585
00:32:19,454 --> 00:32:20,520
Scott: You fill in the holes.

586
00:32:20,660 --> 00:32:24,720
Scott: And the next person who comes and digs in Egypt, it fucking sucks, right?

587
00:32:24,720 --> 00:32:27,339
Scott: Because there is way more dirt than treasure in there now.

588
00:32:27,761 --> 00:32:32,320
Scott: So they need to dig even better than you, Doug, to have a chance of getting anything.

589
00:32:32,660 --> 00:32:38,638
Rym: I once dug 12 tiles from a bag that had a reasonable amount of treasure in it and dug 12 dirt.

590
00:32:39,521 --> 00:32:45,120
Scott: I've also saw some people dig like six tiles out of a bag that was mostly dirt and get like five treasures.

591
00:32:45,660 --> 00:32:47,960
Scott: So it's like there's so much drama when digging.

592
00:32:48,341 --> 00:32:52,640
Scott: But it's just like the drama of doing real archaeology where you go to a site and you start digging.

593
00:32:52,780 --> 00:32:53,808
Scott: It's like, are we going to find anything?

594
00:32:54,050 --> 00:32:55,319
Scott: We don't fucking know.

595
00:32:55,940 --> 00:33:00,198
Scott: And then if you do find something like, "Oh my God, it's a prize amphora completely

596
00:33:00,278 --> 00:33:00,740
Scott: intact.".

597
00:33:00,840 --> 00:33:04,539
Scott: Or, "Oh my God, it's a whole sarcophagus that's plated in gold leaf, only

598
00:33:04,579 --> 00:33:04,720
Scott: shit.".

599
00:33:04,760 --> 00:33:12,360
Rym: So even further to really drive the theme home, it's got all these other little elements, like it has a sheet that tells you what all the treasures are.

600
00:33:12,480 --> 00:33:14,114
Scott: Yeah, they're all real treasures and they have names and stuff.

601
00:33:14,780 --> 00:33:20,739
Rym: There's no bearing on the game, but yet we would read like, "Oh, you just found a blah and a blah and the ancient menorah of blah blah

602
00:33:20,759 --> 00:33:20,980
Rym: blah.".

603
00:33:21,221 --> 00:33:26,120
Scott: Now that's the thing about the game is that the theme of it is so good, but the mechanics are only okay.

604
00:33:26,280 --> 00:33:29,820
Rym: Well, I would say the digging mechanic is what makes you say the mechanics are okay.

605
00:33:29,920 --> 00:33:37,380
Rym: Because the rest of the game, I would like to make a more deterministic game that uses the same front half.

606
00:33:37,480 --> 00:33:38,320
Rym: Everything but the digging.

607
00:33:38,520 --> 00:33:42,520
Scott: It's not just the digging that's random, it's also the cards that are random.

608
00:33:42,880 --> 00:33:46,000
Rym: Well, it's a third in taxes randomness or a web of power randomness.

609
00:33:46,700 --> 00:33:51,180
Scott: So let's say I go to London and I spend a turn researching Egypt, right?

610
00:33:51,741 --> 00:33:54,374
Scott: And then it goes around and I spent a lot of time doing that.

611
00:33:54,455 --> 00:33:55,500
Scott: Everyone else does a bunch of stuff.

612
00:33:55,560 --> 00:33:56,900
Scott: It's finally my turn again, right?

613
00:33:57,362 --> 00:33:59,048
Scott: Now there's four cards available.

614
00:33:59,088 --> 00:34:02,200
Scott: The only thing you can do in Europe is do one of those four cards, pretty much.

615
00:34:03,061 --> 00:34:06,020
Scott: And I look at those four cards and they're all in Moscow.

616
00:34:07,041 --> 00:34:09,733
Scott: And even though I might want to do one of them, I'm in London.

617
00:34:09,813 --> 00:34:11,120
Scott: I just happen to be in London now.

618
00:34:11,341 --> 00:34:13,340
Rym: So suck it up, spend some weeks and go over there.

619
00:34:13,420 --> 00:34:14,998
Scott: So I end up having to spend a bunch of weeks.

620
00:34:15,179 --> 00:34:19,320
Scott: Meanwhile, so now I spend a bunch of weeks to go to Moscow to do this card.

621
00:34:19,900 --> 00:34:23,657
Scott: Then the card that gets flipped over next is, I don't know, Paris.

622
00:34:24,882 --> 00:34:32,976
Scott: Rims already in Paris and it's his turn now and that card only, you know, so he just picks up that card for a lot less weeks than it would have cost me.

623
00:34:33,379 --> 00:34:42,340
Scott: because, and that ends up, it doesn't seem that big a deal, but if it keeps and it might, you know, over time, the whole course of the game, it should even out between the players.

624
00:34:42,460 --> 00:34:48,540
Rym: It is also mitigated heavily by the fact that if you find a good card, it pushes you way up on the time track.

625
00:34:48,841 --> 00:34:54,120
Rym: So whoever fell behind will probably get to do a couple turns in a row and reveal more cards.

626
00:34:54,641 --> 00:34:57,757
Scott: No, that's what I'm saying is if a good card spawns on you, right?

627
00:34:58,660 --> 00:35:02,640
Scott: Not only do you get that card without having to spend a lot of time, but now it's your turn again.

628
00:35:02,720 --> 00:35:06,940
Scott: You can get to do a lot more stuff in a lot less time if the cards turn up your way.

629
00:35:07,180 --> 00:35:10,460
Rym: Well, that's the danger of taking cards and going ahead.

630
00:35:10,902 --> 00:35:14,319
Rym: If you take good cards and go ahead, you basically give everyone else way more card opportunities.

631
00:35:14,800 --> 00:35:17,740
Scott: But you might have no choice depending on what cards are available on your turn.

632
00:35:17,800 --> 00:35:21,060
Scott: So it's not just the digging that's random, it's which cards are there on your turn.

633
00:35:21,421 --> 00:35:25,019
Scott: that is also almost as random as the tiles, but not quite as random.

634
00:35:25,200 --> 00:35:26,952
Rym: Moving will only take like one, two or three weeks.

635
00:35:27,053 --> 00:35:28,100
Rym: Good cards take six.

636
00:35:28,240 --> 00:35:30,380
Rym: I think it's close to being very optimally balanced.

637
00:35:30,740 --> 00:35:32,360
Scott: It's close, but it's not so perfect, right?

638
00:35:32,761 --> 00:35:35,420
Rym: I was watching you make very poor decisions throughout that game.

639
00:35:35,580 --> 00:35:36,380
Scott: No, I was doing fine.

640
00:35:36,980 --> 00:35:45,660
Scott: I mean, so yes, there is decisions to be made that matter a lot, but it's like a half luck, half skill game.

641
00:35:45,980 --> 00:35:49,720
Rym: I think the digging adds 80% of the luck to the game.

642
00:35:49,821 --> 00:35:51,100
Rym: The luck of the card getting.

643
00:35:51,700 --> 00:35:54,780
Scott: I'm just saying the luck of the card getting is not nearly as big as the digging luck.

644
00:35:55,120 --> 00:35:55,846
Rym: I would go beyond that.

645
00:35:55,907 --> 00:35:56,874
Rym: I would say that it's minor.

646
00:35:57,980 --> 00:36:04,140
Scott: I'm saying it is not huge, it is not major, but it is large enough to be significant.

647
00:36:04,300 --> 00:36:05,791
Rym: I wouldn't even say it's that significant.

648
00:36:05,811 --> 00:36:07,120
Rym: I would say it's barely significant.

649
00:36:07,460 --> 00:36:08,560
Scott: I'd say it is significant.

650
00:36:09,260 --> 00:36:11,820
Rym: I think it's a bigger deal in Thurn in taxes and Web of Power.

651
00:36:12,080 --> 00:36:15,193
Scott: It is a bigger deal in those, but it is still a deal.

652
00:36:15,554 --> 00:36:16,036
Scott: It's a deal.

653
00:36:16,317 --> 00:36:16,960
Scott: It's not a big deal?

654
00:36:17,280 --> 00:36:18,473
Rym: Yes, technically you are correct.

655
00:36:18,534 --> 00:36:19,060
Rym: It is a deal.

656
00:36:19,100 --> 00:36:20,564
Scott: It's a deal, right?

657
00:36:21,245 --> 00:36:27,320
Scott: So you could lose a game because bad tiles in your turn, but I also think we were playing four player games, right?

658
00:36:27,420 --> 00:36:28,318
Scott: We've only had two years.

659
00:36:28,881 --> 00:36:35,518
Scott: If you're playing with less players, which it gives you the third year, and also not only more time to do stuff with that third year, right?

660
00:36:36,140 --> 00:36:39,240
Scott: But also more chances at the cards because less competition.

661
00:36:40,102 --> 00:36:43,620
Scott: Also, that it becomes much less, they won't be a deal in less players.

662
00:36:44,721 --> 00:36:51,500
Rym: Interesting thing, we played, this was like the magfest of playing more old style classic German games.

663
00:36:52,080 --> 00:36:58,120
Rym: What I've noticed is that five players or six players is what everyone is shooting for these days because people have bigger groups.

664
00:36:58,620 --> 00:37:05,400
Rym: But, most of the best German games I can think of and most games that have stood the test of time are four player games.

665
00:37:05,680 --> 00:37:07,420
Scott: We played this with four or five players.

666
00:37:07,900 --> 00:37:08,589
Scott: No, we played it with four.

667
00:37:08,629 --> 00:37:09,379
Rym: It only takes up to four.

668
00:37:11,844 --> 00:37:14,719
Rym: Most of the games we played at this magfest take four max.

669
00:37:15,020 --> 00:37:16,726
Scott: I think this is best with two or three.

670
00:37:17,087 --> 00:37:20,700
Scott: I think four stresses the resources of the game too much.

671
00:37:21,200 --> 00:37:27,120
Scott: And it makes the digging much more punishing because now you've got the same amount of competition for the same amount of treasure.

672
00:37:27,300 --> 00:37:30,434
Scott: They don't put in more treasures and more dirt in more player game.

673
00:37:30,474 --> 00:37:31,600
Scott: It's the same bag, right?

674
00:37:32,360 --> 00:37:36,528
Rym: Because this game is a race, it is not highly political.

675
00:37:36,949 --> 00:37:43,340
Rym: so it does not fall into the three player game trap where a three player game is actually a two player game plus a safety monkey.

676
00:37:44,500 --> 00:37:47,560
Rym: So, yes, I agree this game is probably a lot better with three player.

677
00:37:47,760 --> 00:37:48,603
Scott: Just because it will be more fun.

678
00:37:48,663 --> 00:37:53,560
Scott: More people will get a chance to go in the bag and get treasures even though the scores will be higher.

679
00:37:53,940 --> 00:37:55,045
Scott: You'll get to do more stuff.

680
00:37:55,527 --> 00:37:57,957
Scott: It will just be more enjoyable with more players.

681
00:37:57,997 --> 00:37:58,379
Scott: Less players.

682
00:37:58,981 --> 00:38:04,600
Rym: It's kind of like how Bonanza is real fun with six and seven but it's also kind of broken.

683
00:38:05,140 --> 00:38:09,280
Rym: Bonanza with five is ideal and perfect and one of my favorite games.

684
00:38:09,560 --> 00:38:10,988
Scott: I think this game is ideal with three.

685
00:38:11,109 --> 00:38:13,100
Scott: Even two I think this game can be really good.

686
00:38:13,660 --> 00:38:15,953
Rym: Two would be real interesting.

687
00:38:16,034 --> 00:38:16,959
Scott: I haven't played it with two.

688
00:38:17,300 --> 00:38:19,513
Scott: I think three is the ideal but I still think two is good.

689
00:38:19,593 --> 00:38:20,780
Scott: I would prefer two to the four.

690
00:38:21,220 --> 00:38:24,180
Rym: Board Game Geek says best with three to four which is interesting.

691
00:38:24,962 --> 00:38:27,839
Scott: I wonder if there's any special rules for the two because we didn't actually play the two.

692
00:38:28,802 --> 00:38:30,940
Scott: But the three I think is the sweet spot.

693
00:38:31,080 --> 00:38:33,170
Rym: Yeah, there's a big difference between three and four player.

694
00:38:33,231 --> 00:38:35,060
Rym: I wouldn't say best with three to four.

695
00:38:35,460 --> 00:38:40,200
Scott: Yeah, I think best with three and then four is kind of like it's playable but it's not as good as the three.

696
00:38:40,380 --> 00:38:46,720
Rym: But if you're especially an aspiring game designer, you should play this game for nothing else than to see a game that so perfectly matches theme.

697
00:38:47,060 --> 00:38:50,540
Scott: Yeah, the mechanic theme meshing here is so perfect.

698
00:38:50,800 --> 00:38:51,440
Rym: Here's another example.

699
00:38:51,480 --> 00:38:53,800
Scott: There are so few games that line it up so well.

700
00:38:53,820 --> 00:38:55,207
Rym: There's a bunch of other parts.

701
00:38:55,227 --> 00:38:56,594
Rym: We didn't obviously tell you the whole rules.

702
00:38:57,840 --> 00:39:01,700
Scott: Like when you play Puerto Rico and you choose Craftsman, do you really feel like you're crafting?

703
00:39:01,960 --> 00:39:05,430
Scott: No, but when you choose to dig and spend six weeks digging in Egypt.

704
00:39:05,470 --> 00:39:08,880
Scott: in this game, you feel like you're spending six weeks digging in Egypt.

705
00:39:09,020 --> 00:39:13,000
Scott: And when you go around Europe researching, you feel like you're traveling around Europe researching.

706
00:39:13,882 --> 00:39:15,560
Rym: But there's also these exhibitions.

707
00:39:15,941 --> 00:39:22,580
Rym: So you'll be digging in Egypt and suddenly you see, oh, there's an exposition going on in London right now.

708
00:39:22,780 --> 00:39:36,599
Rym: And if you've got the stuff to be able to exhibit there to loan to their museum, you've got to get your ass back to London, be there before anyone else who also has the right goods, lend your stuff to the museum and you have to spend three weeks at the exposition.

709
00:39:38,044 --> 00:39:38,457
Scott: The expo.

710
00:39:38,881 --> 00:39:39,551
Scott: Yes, expo.

711
00:39:40,885 --> 00:39:42,220
Rym: Because I'm doing expeditions.

712
00:39:42,220 --> 00:39:44,034
Scott: I think it's actually just exhibit in a museum.

713
00:39:44,054 --> 00:39:44,799
Scott: It's not an expo.

714
00:39:45,000 --> 00:39:50,620
Scott: But yeah, there's all kinds of side things that you can do that are kind of interesting and fun to get more victory points.

715
00:39:50,761 --> 00:39:52,319
Rym: And they're all so tight with the theme.

716
00:39:53,081 --> 00:40:02,740
Rym: But also the mechanic of you spend time going around a board is a very interesting self-tuning mechanic that you could use.

717
00:40:02,981 --> 00:40:04,960
Rym: It's a lot of old German games had stuff like that.

718
00:40:05,661 --> 00:40:14,760
Rym: I recall I started playing a bunch of them again, where even if the game wasn't like super prescriptively designed for balance, they'll have these mechanics where anyone gets too far ahead.

719
00:40:14,860 --> 00:40:17,959
Rym: It's not like a traditional rubber band that just sort of pulls you up.

720
00:40:18,421 --> 00:40:23,292
Rym: But it's more like the more powerful strategies have an intrinsic game cost.

721
00:40:23,553 --> 00:40:28,040
Rym: that sort of causes them to balance out very nicely, even if you didn't think about it too closely.

722
00:40:28,380 --> 00:40:32,920
Scott: I think what makes this game such a good thing, if you can find a copy, buy it.

723
00:40:33,200 --> 00:40:41,660
Scott: Because on the one hand, it is a competitive game, though it's not super perfect, amazing competitive, like I say, a netrunner or something like that.

724
00:40:41,981 --> 00:40:50,300
Scott: But it's competitive enough that someone who likes to play games to win can play this game and think a lot about strategies and make interesting decisions and have a good time.

725
00:40:51,101 --> 00:41:03,680
Scott: But also because the theme and the mechanic match so well and the fun are reaching in the bag, that person who usually was only willing to play Cards Against Humanity or maybe Camel Up, Camel Cup, something like that.

726
00:41:04,204 --> 00:41:05,419
Rym: It's canonically Camel Up.

727
00:41:06,122 --> 00:41:18,339
Scott: Someone who's usually only playing the easier, more luck-based, not skilled, not hardcore games like Camel Up, you can get them to play this game because it's so fun to go in the bag and do the things.

728
00:41:19,640 --> 00:41:26,000
Scott: And then you can use this to get both of those people to play the game together and have a good time without that conflict that usually happens.

729
00:41:26,481 --> 00:41:28,660
Scott: There's not a lot of games in that sweet spot.

730
00:41:28,860 --> 00:41:29,980
Rym: You'll see a neat design pattern.

731
00:41:30,281 --> 00:41:39,860
Rym: There's a lot of games where you can take some number of things, and if you're clever, you can make a combo of the exact values of them.

732
00:41:40,240 --> 00:41:41,243
Rym: Like Power Grid is an example.

733
00:41:41,283 --> 00:41:49,539
Rym: Power Grid is a game where you can spend exactly all of your money if you're very clever a lot of the time, and it's a huge advantage if you did so.

734
00:41:49,800 --> 00:42:04,875
Rym: If you set the stage for that play to happen later, this game does that in the sense that if you fall way behind in time, you might be able to look at the board and come up with a combo where you get to take two or three turns, and then you land directly on top of someone.

735
00:42:04,996 --> 00:42:05,620
Rym: Exactly.

736
00:42:06,240 --> 00:42:11,940
Rym: If you land on top of someone on the time thing, top is last place, so you get to take yet another turn.

737
00:42:13,402 --> 00:42:15,229
Rym: I feel like a heuristic to know who's doing.

738
00:42:15,269 --> 00:42:24,300
Rym: well is who landed on top of another player the most, because that is the person who's doing the Power Grid thing of spending exactly all of their money more than once in the game.

739
00:42:24,300 --> 00:42:25,044
Scott: Right, so think about it.

740
00:42:25,064 --> 00:42:28,480
Scott: You're sitting there looking at the board, and you see a card you really want, right?

741
00:42:28,520 --> 00:42:35,048
Scott: And there's three cards you don't really want so much, so you go and you're in Europe, you're not ready to dig anything yet, so you just go and get the card you really want.

742
00:42:35,068 --> 00:42:37,720
Scott: You move two spaces and take it for five turns.

743
00:42:37,800 --> 00:42:40,260
Scott: Now it's not your turn anymore, but you didn't pay attention.

744
00:42:40,380 --> 00:42:46,599
Scott: One of those cards you didn't want was on the spot you spawned and only cost one week to pick up.

745
00:42:47,161 --> 00:42:47,502
Rym: Even though

746
00:42:47,643 --> 00:43:01,460
Scott: it wasn't a great card that you really wanted, you could have gotten that card basically for free, but because you weren't paying attention, you didn't get it, and you just let it sit there, and it's like you could have had two cards, instead you only got one card because you weren't being careful.

747
00:43:01,860 --> 00:43:16,440
Rym: So that is sort of almost a common design pattern, irrespective of the mechanic that causes it, of does the game have a mechanism to reward the player for being exact about something that's difficult to predict or difficult to calculate?

748
00:43:17,064 --> 00:43:19,179
Rym: Power Grid does it, and this game does it.

749
00:43:19,860 --> 00:43:27,490
Rym: And I wanted to add a new thing to the way we review board games, because on one of the panels I was on, that Scott was not on at MagFest, super smart guy.

750
00:43:27,811 --> 00:43:30,300
Rym: Luke Peterschmidt at Fundo11 said something really interesting.

751
00:43:31,920 --> 00:43:44,489
Rym: Most tabletop games, like commercial ones, not necessarily the weirdo German ones we play, but in general, they pretty much assume that the game's got three to five plays tops, and that people really won't play it.

752
00:43:44,529 --> 00:43:46,420
Rym: much beyond that, except maybe bringing it out.

753
00:43:47,100 --> 00:43:52,080
Rym: Games that get past that three plays barrier are real close to being classics for all time.

754
00:43:53,180 --> 00:44:07,160
Rym: If you're talking about games above a certain level of complexity, but below a certain other arbitrary, there's a lot more, I'm taking this quote kind of out of context, I think this game has four to five more plays by me before I'm done with it.

755
00:44:07,501 --> 00:44:23,080
Scott: I think the number of plays this game has is entirely dependent on how many friends you have, because you might get tired of digging in that bag, and it might lose its excitement a bit, but if you bring some new people in, it can refresh in the excitement, because reaching in that bag is just so awesome.

756
00:44:23,220 --> 00:44:30,140
Rym: So thus, the way I would put that is, this game has three to five plays from a purely intellectual, "I'm a gamer playing this game" perspective.

757
00:44:30,200 --> 00:44:33,220
Scott: And any new person is going to want to play it at least two to three times.

758
00:44:33,461 --> 00:44:35,246
Rym: But it has unlimited play.

759
00:44:35,286 --> 00:44:41,919
Rym: for me, as Scott was alluding to, in that if I'm with some people who have never played this game, and I own this game, I'll just bust it out.

760
00:44:43,481 --> 00:44:46,719
Scott: You're not going to bust it out with two people who've played it before and one who hasn't?

761
00:44:46,884 --> 00:44:47,040
Scott: Nope.

762
00:44:47,180 --> 00:44:52,899
Scott: But one who has played it before and two or three who haven't, yes, you're going to bust it out, because they're going to have so much fun going in the bag.

763
00:44:53,240 --> 00:44:53,600
Rym: Definitely.

764
00:44:53,920 --> 00:44:55,813
Scott: And digging into Egypt and finding nothing.

765
00:44:56,055 --> 00:44:56,760
Scott: Dirt, dirt, dirt.

766
00:44:57,080 --> 00:45:00,595
Scott: And everyone's chanting when you go in the bag, all the other players are like, "Dirt!

767
00:45:00,937 --> 00:45:01,198
Scott: Dirt!

768
00:45:01,539 --> 00:45:01,700
Scott: Dirt!".

769
00:45:01,700 --> 00:45:03,328
Rym: And at one point, Scott took the bag.

770
00:45:03,368 --> 00:45:05,760
Rym: I was about to dig into and put a curse on it.

771
00:45:05,880 --> 00:45:08,059
Rym: And sure enough, I drew like nine fucking dirt.

772
00:45:08,882 --> 00:45:09,204
Scott: Curses!

773
00:45:09,566 --> 00:45:11,416
Scott: King Tut, he got you!

774
00:45:11,677 --> 00:45:12,080
Scott: King Tut!

775
00:45:13,301 --> 00:45:26,160
Rym: So we're going to try to do that in all of our reviews from now on, of really talk about how many plays this game has got in it, because I feel like that's one thing, that's a metric that we could have used a lot more, we could have used that very effectively in our older game reviews.

776
00:45:26,602 --> 00:45:34,772
Rym: I'm trying to go back and think about some of those games, because then, a couple of years down the road, we can go back and say, "Hey, how many times did we play that game?

777
00:45:35,134 --> 00:45:39,980
Rym: Was it really five players, or was there some high-end strategy we didn't think about?

778
00:45:40,561 --> 00:45:41,147
Rym: Did we play it

779
00:45:41,187 --> 00:45:41,490
Rym: more?".

780
00:45:42,480 --> 00:45:45,953
Rym: Because T&E right now is one of the... T&E and Puerto Rico still have Infinity.

781
00:45:45,973 --> 00:45:46,780
Rym: I'll play those right now.

782
00:45:49,343 --> 00:45:52,580
Scott: But there's also games that could have a lot of plays and we just don't for whatever reason.

783
00:45:54,202 --> 00:45:56,313
Scott: We could play Lost Cities just whenever.

784
00:45:56,333 --> 00:45:57,418
Scott: We just don't.

